Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?[DOSKUTSU]=20dos:=20Phase=209=20wave=204=20patc?=
 =?UTF-8?q?h=200016=20=E2=80=94=20pin=20VBE=20display-start=20to=20(0,0)?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Wave 3's Fix A (patch 0014) made `populate_fb_state_for_direct_fb`
always pick `data->page_offset[0]` as the WRITE target — under the
assumption that "page 0" of the LFB is also the displayed page. On
real Cirrus + UNIVBE that assumption is wrong: the BIOS's mode-set
leaves the display-start scan-line offset wherever the previous mode
left it, so writes to LFB offset 0 land on a non-displayed page and
the user sees the boot Loading splash stick forever despite 160+
fast-path flushes per the wave-3 cirrus3 capture.

Patch 0014 also force-disabled page-flipping when SDL_HINT_DOS_PREFER_LFB
is set, which routed the mode-set into the `else` branch that does NOT
call VBE 0x4F07. That's how the BIOS-controlled offset never gets
zeroed — the only existing 0x4F07 call (line ~882) lives inside the
page-flip branch, gated behind `prefer_lfb_no_flip`.

Two-part fix:

1. SDL_dosmodes.c: after the mode-set succeeds (use_lfb true), call
   VBE function 0x4F07 subfunction 0 with X=0,Y=0 unconditionally.
   This forces the displayed page to LFB offset 0 regardless of what
   the BIOS left behind. Idempotent with the page-flip branch's
   existing call (same arguments). Failure is logged but not fatal —
   pre-VBE-1.2 BIOSes lacked 0x4F07, but every BIOS we'd actually
   target supports it.

2. SDL_dosframebuffer.c: record the BIOS-reported LFB physical
   address in `fb_state.vram_phys` instead of the sentinel 0 patch
   0014 left there. Operationally inert (the fast-path guard accepts
   either vram_ptr or vram_phys), but the wave-3 SDLDBG.LOG line 52
   showing `vram_phys=0x00000000` was misleading during the
   visual-stuck investigation. With this fix the diag now reports
   the actual LFB base (e.g. 0x78000000 on Cirrus, 0xe0000000 on
   DOSBox-X parity), making "is the LFB mapping correct?" answerable
   from the log alone.

Verified under DOSBox-X parity smoke (build/stage/SDLDBG.LOG):
  display-start pinned to (0,0) via VBE 0x4F07: ax=0x004F
  CreateWindowFramebuffer #1 (exit fast): direct_fb=1 ... vram_phys=0xe0000000
  DOSVESA-FB-INIT: ... vram_phys=0xe0000000 vram_ptr=0xdfc00000

Title scene renders full-window with no upper-left corner artifact
and no Loading-screen stick — matches wave-2's lever0b-title.png
baseline. fastpath-timing blocks continue to flow normally
(~1.2 ms/flush in DOSBox-X).

Why DOS needs this
------------------
Real Cirrus + UNIVBE (g2k Cirrus configuration) and possibly other
real-HW VBE BIOSes do not zero the display-start register on a fresh
mode-set. Without an explicit VBE 0x4F07 call the displayed page
remains at whatever the BIOS left it at, and writes via the LFB
nearptr to "page 0" land out of sight. DOSBox-X's emulated VBE clears
display-start to (0,0) on mode-set so this is invisible under parity
testing — only surfaces on real HW.

Local-only patch per workspace policy (memory note "SDL upstream —
local patches only"): never PR'd upstream.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c | 13 +++++++-
 src/video/dos/SDL_dosmodes.c       | 50 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 2 files changed, 62 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c b/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c
index e76f9d524..2f4dfcb08 100644
--- a/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c
+++ b/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c
@@ -363,7 +363,18 @@ static bool populate_fb_state_for_direct_fb(SDL_VideoDevice *device,
         // proper double-buffering later, restore VBE PageSet plumbing
         // then.
         fb_state.vram_ptr = (Uint8 *)DOS_PhysicalToLinear(data->mapping.address) + data->page_offset[0];
-        fb_state.vram_phys = 0;
+        // DOSKUTSU patch 0016: record the BIOS-reported LFB physical
+        // address (e.g. 0x78000000 on the cirrus3 capture) instead of the
+        // sentinel 0 patch 0014 left here. The fast-path guard at the
+        // bottom of UpdateWindowFramebuffer accepts either vram_ptr OR
+        // vram_phys as proof of "we have a destination", so the previous
+        // value worked operationally — but the diagnostic line in
+        // SDLDBG.LOG (DOSVESA-FB-INIT vram_phys=...) carried a misleading
+        // 0x00000000, which made it look like the LFB mapping itself was
+        // bad during the wave-3 visual-stuck investigation. Recording
+        // the real LFB base makes the diag accurate without changing
+        // runtime behaviour.
+        fb_state.vram_phys = (Uint32)data->mapping.address + data->page_offset[0];
         fb_state.use_dosmemput = false;
         fb_state.banked_multibank = false;
     } else {
diff --git a/src/video/dos/SDL_dosmodes.c b/src/video/dos/SDL_dosmodes.c
index dd4e7a6b5..72bb62f77 100644
--- a/src/video/dos/SDL_dosmodes.c
+++ b/src/video/dos/SDL_dosmodes.c
@@ -892,6 +892,56 @@ bool DOSVESA_SetDisplayMode(SDL_VideoDevice *device, SDL_VideoDisplay *sdl_displ
         data->page_offset[1] = 0;
     }
 
+    // DOSKUTSU patch 0016 (Phase 9 wave 4, fixes Fix A's broken assumption):
+    // unconditionally pin the displayed page to LFB offset (0,0) for any
+    // successful LFB mode-set. The original page-flip block above only
+    // calls VBE 0x4F07 inside its true branch, so when patch 0014's
+    // `prefer_lfb_no_flip` gate forces us into the `else` branch the BIOS
+    // never receives a Set-Display-Start call and the displayed page
+    // retains whatever scan-line offset the BIOS left it at on mode-set.
+    //
+    // Wave-3 real-Cirrus capture (/tmp/cirrus3 SDLDBG.LOG): the engine
+    // wrote into LFB offset 0 (page_offset[0]) at vram_ptr=0x77c00000 for
+    // 160+ flips, but the user saw the boot Loading splash stuck and
+    // never updated. Inference: Cirrus's BIOS left display-start pointing
+    // at a different page after mode-set, so writes to "page 0" landed in
+    // a non-displayed page. Wave-2 saw "Loading + flashes" on the same
+    // hardware — that pattern matches page 1 being the displayed page and
+    // the per-flush VBE 0x4F07 swap intermittently bringing page 0 into
+    // view.
+    //
+    // The fix: after the BIOS mode-set succeeds, call VBE 0x4F07
+    // subfunction 0 with X=0,Y=0 to FORCE display-start to LFB offset 0.
+    // Now "page 0" IS the displayed page, regardless of what the BIOS
+    // left behind. This is unconditional for LFB modes (use_lfb true)
+    // and only logs a soft warning if the BIOS rejects the call — older
+    // VBE 1.0 ROMs lacked function 0x4F07 but every VBE 1.2+ BIOS we'd
+    // actually run on supports it.
+    //
+    // Why it's safe to do twice when the page-flip branch above also
+    // called it: VBE 0x4F07 with the same arguments is idempotent. The
+    // duplication exists for the (unlikely) future case where someone
+    // reverts patch 0014 and wants page-flipping back; the above branch
+    // sets up page_offset[1] correctly and starts at page 0, this block
+    // re-asserts (0,0) for the no-page-flip case.
+    if (use_lfb) {
+        __dpmi_regs sds_regs;
+        SDL_zero(sds_regs);
+        sds_regs.x.ax = 0x4F07;
+        sds_regs.x.bx = 0x0000; // BH=0 set display start, BL=0 wait for retrace
+        sds_regs.x.cx = 0;      // first pixel in scan line
+        sds_regs.x.dx = 0;      // first scan line
+        __dpmi_int(0x10, &sds_regs);
+        if ((sds_regs.x.ax & 0x00FF) == 0x004F) {
+            DOSKUTSU_MODES_LOG("display-start pinned to (0,0) via VBE 0x4F07: ax=0x%04X",
+                               sds_regs.x.ax);
+        } else {
+            DOSKUTSU_MODES_LOG("display-start force FAILED (VBE 0x4F07 unsupported?): ax=0x%04X "
+                               "-- continuing; visible page may be wrong",
+                               sds_regs.x.ax);
+        }
+    }
+
     if (SDL_GetMouse()->internal != NULL) { // internal != NULL) == int 33h services available.
         regs.x.ax = 0x7;                    // set mouse min/max horizontal position.
         regs.x.cx = 0;
